8:
Shut it! Nobody likes you, kid. We're
leaving you here. You're on your own.
9:
D-don't give me those eyes! You
itching for another beating, or what?!
10: Please... Not again... Don't hit me.
12:
It hurts so much... Like I'm going to
die... I don't... I don't want to die!
20:
Ah. What a quiet and peaceful town.
How serene.
26:
Why hello there, everyone. On your
way home?
29: Yeah. Are you doing anything, Weihu?
33:
Not particularly. Would you mind if I
joined you? We could chat on the
way.
37:
Sure. We weren't really doing
anything anyway.
41:
No gory crime stories though, okay?
...Then again, those are probably all
you've got.
45:
I suppose that might be the case.
Can't be helped, given the place I
was born.
49: You spent your whole life there, huh?
52:
That I did. I was an orphan. I had my
hands full just keeping all those
deranged, lunatic adults out of my
life, haha.
56:
...Yikes. Doesn't sound like a great
environment to be in.
59:
We orphans made do with what we
had. There were a lot of us, so we
formed communes. Helped each
other survive.
61:
We taught each other. Some of us
went on to live upstanding lives. I
even have some acquaintances in
the Gaean government!
67:
Though not all were so fortunate.
Many didn't even survive.
75:
Hehe. Indeed. I was ousted from the
commune. Everyone always hated
me. Ever since I was young.
78:
It perplexes me to this day—why did
people hate me so much? Hmm.
82:
I'm just impressed things didn't turn
out worse for you, all things
considered.
86:
Anyway, for those who are cast out,
there's usually one clear-cut path to
walk: joining an organization like the
one we fought before.
88:
Then it begins—the fighting for your
life. A daily struggle, all alone, until
the moment of your death. No
companionship. A battle with
destiny you are doomed to lose.
91:
And I WAS supposed to lose there,
you see. But I was cast out from
even the outcasts, and now I'm here.
In another world.
95:
It sounds like you don't feel
comfortable here yet. Is that right?
100:
Perhaps. That's an interesting way of
putting it.
102:
You no-good thief! What stupid
excuse do you have for us this time,
huh? Let's hear it!
105:
I... I didn't steal anything! You have
no proof!
106:
Y-you guys are just a bunch of
third-rate adventurers, anyway! No
one will believe you!
117: Oh yes. I very much am.
120:
Who the hell are you? This has
nothing to do with you!
123:
You seem like quite the formidable
group of adventurers! The best this
city has to offer, no doubt.
125:
I imagine you're confident in your
own skills. Surely one more
opponent would be trivial for you to
handle?
128: You want to pick a fight with us, huh?
131:
Yes, precisely. Doesn't matter who,
where, or why, really. Just looking for
a good old-fashioned rumble.
141:
You won't even draw your weapons?
Fascinating.
144:
Look around. The eyes of the public
are fixed upon you.
146:
The more you hurt others, the more
those around you will resent you.
Such is your fate if you follow down
this path.
152:
Ah. I could almost feel their
gratitude for the valuable lesson I
taught them. Helping others truly is
rewarding.
155:
Uh-huh. I think I'm starting to get
why people don't like you.
159:
Hehe. I would say I handled the
situation rather smoothly this time. I
took great inspiration from when
you helped me, Nimbus.
164:
Though, uh... Helping those guys
wasn't really your main goal, was it?
168:
That's true. But either way, who's to
say what was the truth? Was the
man really a thief? Were the
adventurers lying? Who knows.
170:
If only they had humored me and
drawn their weapons. That would
have been fun.
175:
For a guy who says he's scared of
death, you sure enjoy dancing with
it...
179:
I AM scared of death. I absolutely do
not wish to die—just like every other
normal person, no?
182:
Anyway. This really is a lovely city.
Utterly unlike my hometown—in all
the good ways.
185:
And yet... I don't feel comfortable
here. It's exactly as you said.
187:
The truth is that I am horrifically
bored. Perhaps my heart longs for
violence... Just like the deranged
adults I ran away from.
190: Do you regret taking me in?
195:
First, just a reminder of what Stella
said earlier. No dying.
198:
And... I think the answer to that
question is obviously "no."
203:
Come on, man. We knew exactly
what kind of person you were from
the outset—didn't exactly have great
expectations for you.
210:
You really are a bizarre lot, do you
know that? I guess it flows down
from the top of your
organization—understandable, with
a boss like Stella.
214:
Again, to reiterate, we are NOT the
mafia, and Stella is not our boss.
217:
Yes, yes. Of course. I understand.
Yours is a group that flagrantly
defies any attempts to describe it!
220:
But I think I'm beginning to
understand you.
